name: Lake Street Single Family Home
description:
Our full-time home (available when we are away), is your perfect place to call "home base" as you explore the city or visit friends.

The space
Great open floor plan home on a quiet tree lined street in one of San Francisco's most coveted neighborhoods. Walking distance to the Presidio, Mountain Lake Park, Laurel Village, Sacramento St shopping and Golden Gate Park. Easy walk to many cafes and restaurants.

The first level features a sunny gourmet kitchen with top-of-the-line appliances, open kitchen/dining area/family area, a lovely foyer, living room with flat panel TV/DirectTV, and a full bathroom with a large whirlpool soaking tub. There is also a small laundry room on this level. There is a deck off kitchen with a Weber grill and the small backyard features a grassy area and patio seating. The second floor has 3 BR's - 1st BR with a Queen Bed, 2nd BR has a full bed and 3rd BR has a twin bed + a twin trundle. A pack-n-play is also available.

name: Sunny 4-Bedroom Family Home Central SF Location
description:
Enjoy the best of urban village living in our light, spacious, 4-bedroom, 2 & 1/2 bath home in the heart of Bernal Heights, only two blocks from the restaurants, shops and galleries of Cortland Street. It's a short walk to the amazing Mission for food and drink and Bernal Hill for hiking and amazing views. Our home comfortably accommodates a family, or a larger group. Easy street parking with no residential parking permit required. Close to transit (BART, MUNI) and major freeways (101 and 280).

The space
This beautiful 4-bedroom, 2 1/2 bath home is nestled in the hip 'urban village' of Bernal Heights in San Francisco. The house is beautifully remodeled, with an open kitchen with granite countertops, brand new appliances, and hardwood floors. The master bedroom is spacious and has a queen-sized bed. The second bedroom is smaller, with a full-size bed (sleeps 2) and a desk. The third bedroom is perfect for a child with a twin loft bed, desk, and bookcase. The four
neighborhood_overview: Bernal Heights is a chic urban village full of restaurants, shops, and galleries. Spend your days wandering the cafes and shops of Cortland Street, or exploring the numerious gardens and parks the neighborhood has to offer. Definitely do not miss the view from the top of Bernal Hill  -- it offers unparalelled views of the city of San Francisco and San Francisco Bay. It's also one of the only places you can see both the Golden Gate Bridge and the Bay Bridge from one spot!
host_about: We are a tight-knit family of four with two wonderful, school-aged girls. This is our San Francisco home where, when we are traveling for business or personal reasons, we love having people from all over the world stay and enjoy our home, our neighborhood and our city!

name: Potrero Paradise with Stunning Views and Hot Tub
description:
Enjoy San Francisco's sunniest neighborhood, Potrero Hill, in this luxurious and charming 3-story Mediterranean style retreat. 5 outdoor patios/decks all with amazing views including from the always ready hot tub.

The home is situated with easy access to every part of San Francisco including the Mission District, Oracle Park, and Warriors Stadium. It is walking distance to SF General Hospital and just over a mile from USCF's Mission Bay campus.

In addition to the comfortable and spacious bedrooms, there is an office with a monitor for your use. Garage and full laundry room. Peloton too!

This spacious three-story, three bedroom home and its five patios and balconies feature stunning views of Twin Peaks, Downtown, East Bay, and ATT Park. The house is set away from the street with a gracious front patio/garden and is very quiet.

Great for work groups! Less than 2 miles from Moscone Convention Center and easy access to public transportation,
neighborhood_overview:
The house is set away from the street near the top of Potrero Hill, a quiet and walkable neighborhood known for its sunny weather, charming eateries, hip bars, and quaint boutiques. Visit the nearby Museum of Craft and Design, or head to the neighboring Mission District.

The home is also convenient to Moscone Convention Center, SoMa, Oracle Park (Giants) and Chase Center (Warriors).

Parking is plentiful outside the home and no permit is required. 1 car garage also available.
host_about:
I'm a Bay Area Serial Internet Entrepreneur, best known for Match Online Dating, TrustArc, and now BabyQuip, baby equipment rental marketplace.   I enjoy meeting new entrepreneurs and  business people as well as tourists and work hard to be sure everyone has a positive experience in my home.  

My homes are in cities named by the Spanish for Saint Francis of Assisi:  San Francisco and Santa Fe  (Santa Fe's full name is  La Villa Real de la Santa FÃÂ© de San Francisco de AsÃÂ­s (Ã¢â¬ÅThe Royal Town of the Holy Faith of St. Francis of AssisiÃ¢â¬Â).

My San Francisco home is on Potrero Hill.  I love the home's gardens and fantastic views which you can see from five different patios or decks.  My guests enjoy the combination of luxury and elegance with comfortable charm.

My other homes are in Santa Fe, New Mexico, where I grew up.  The two homes on Garcia St., Gorgeous on Garcia and Casa Kateri, in the Historic East Side of Santa Fe, are truly "Santa Fe Style" with vigas (ceiling beams), Kiva fireplace, wood floors and thick adobe walls.  The setting is spectacular in the heart of old Santa Fe with easy access to the museums, art, hiking trails, and plaza.  Casa Laguna is in the Quail Run resort community in Santa Fe, just a few miles from town.  There you can access the golf course, tennis/pickle ball courts, swimming pool, and wonderful trail system.

As you can see from my reviews, many first-time Airbnb guests have enjoyed my homes. If you are new to Airbnb (or not) and want to book one of my listings, please consider these 'pro tips' gleaned from my Airbnb experiences...both, as a host and as a guest:

1) Read the Airbnb FAQs thoroughly and feel free to ask questions. Hosts with popular listings appreciate it when prospective guests ask questions unique to their travel situation and/or the listing in question. 

2) PLEASE thoroughly read through my listings. I assure you that your questions about parking, public transportation, check in/out, etc. have been included in the listings.

3)  Tell me about yourself.  Since you may have few/no reviews, hosts like me must make a guess as to what sort of guest(s) you might be (and some hosts won't even consider people new to Airbnb). In the absence of a review, you might consider the following to ensure I (other hosts) will feel comfortable approving your request:

Ã¢â¬Â¢ in your initial note, it is appreciated when you include what your plans are during your stay (sightseeing, attending a conference, partying at clubs, etc) 
Ã¢â¬Â¢ include assuring comments about how you will treat my home (i.e. "I will treat your home with the same respect I treat mine") 
Ã¢â¬Â¢ let me know you've read the house rules, and that they are agreeable to you (this is a must, please)

4) Finally...I, like other busy hosts, keep my calendar up to date! So, if Airbnb is showing my listings as available for your dates - the place is available! If my listing suits your needs, it is best to send the booking request right off. If you hesitate, the other person looking at my place for your dates will get it!

Hope this is helpful. Welcome!

description:
We love our home and hope you will, too. It's light, super clean (all AirBNB cleaning requirements...and then some), pretty modern, and very comfortable. We've got all the amenities, including a backyard, and can sleep 4 - 6. We live in a great neighborhood that has easy access to parks, shops and restaurants on Clement and Haight Street.

The space
Enjoy our beautiful home in the Inner Richmond neighborhood of San Francisco, just a few short blocks from Golden Gate Park, near University of San Francisco.

Our home was built in 1936, styled after Rousseau, a well-known architect, famous for his inner light-well/courtyard. Our house has a central atrium that spreads light through the main parts of the house. It has a great layout, with plenty of room to spread out. We love our home and think you will too.

name: Sweet Victorian Charmer with Views
description:
Perched high up on 28th St. with stunning views of downtown and the Bay Bridge from our dining room, living room, kitchen and deck our home can be yours while we're away in December. Parking is free and readily available - no kidding - and public transportation is so close you can see the bus stop from the front door. If you'd like to settle into our little gem after a hard day of sightseeing, let us know!

The space
Our home is more than 100 years old and we love its old world charm. It has lots of wood and lots of windows and an open floor plan so you can enjoy the panoramic view from the kitchen, dining and livingrooms. There is a wrap around deck with plants, a barbeque and a table and chairs - great for breakfast or lunch in good weather. The bedroom has a double bed and we have a double futon mattress that you're welcome to use in the living room. There is one full bathroom.

With garden, deck, and stunning views you might just want to experienc
neighborhood_overview:
We live in a great part of San Francisco. The views are lovely, the air is fresh, the people are friendly, and parking is free and readily available in our part of Noe Valley (as opposed to many other parts of our neighborhood and the city).

We're close to great dining and neighborhood shopping. 24th Street in "downtown" Noe Valley is one of the most delightful neighborhoods in San Francisco. It's like being in a small town in the midst of a big city.

We're also convenient to the "Big City" and to all parts of the Bay Area. We are close to public transportation and to highways that can easily get you to nearby cities and attractions if you have a car. (See "Getting Around" for more details.)

If you're up for it, I welcome the opportunity to practice with you.

description:
Our house is a two story building with yard on a quiet street and in a very friendly, family-oriented area. We rent it out when we are away during the summer.

The space
Our house has a yard with herbs, lemons and apples. It is located in a friendly neighborhood in San Francisco, 5 minutes walk from the largest farmers' market and the largest flea market in the bay area (Alemany Market). The house has two bedrooms, two bathrooms and one spacious living/dining room, opening into a wide and sunny kitchen. The room downstairs has a queen size bed and an en-suite bathroom with shower, sink and toilet and opens into our yard. The master bedroom upstairs has a king size bed and all mattresses are very comfortable.
In the garage you can do your laundry (large washer and dryer).
We love to cook, have good pots and lots of cookbooks. If you'd rather eat out, you will be 5 minutes walk from Cortland Avenue where you can dine out to your heart content, do your fo
neighborhood_overview: I love its friendly atmosphere and the many eateries.  Well connected with Downtown SF and many other destinations in the city.
host_about:
Hi, my name is Cecilia. I am from Rome but live in San Francisco. I love good food, books about history, philosophy, art, anthropology, and film. I dream about having free time to read good novels. I love classical music, jazz, arabic music, and traditional indian dance. My favorite travel destination: a hammock in the shade near the sea, preferably on a hill, a cold tea with lemon and sugar and a good book and also the desire to sleep without a work deadline. 
As a guest I am independent and curious. As a host I like clear communication and would like for my guest to feel at home and welcome. 
My motto: a day at the time.

name: Quiet Cozy Castro Cottage
description:
Our place is in the heart of the Castro district, the epicenter of Gay culture in San Francisco. We are close to many restaurants and clubs.

The house is historic, built in 1871 by a prominent local family. It was moved from the street to the back of the property and is quiet and tranquil. We appreciate that our neighbors all live close by, and keep a quiet house.

The space
Charming 1871 two-floor cottage with one cat in the heart of the Castro neighborhood (on Hartford Street, between 18th and 19th Street) easy walking distance to Muni transportation and a quiet and convenient refuge from the Castro excitement. The home is in private gated area, is very quiet and surrounded by trees and flowering plants, and it overlooks a private courtyard with two small decorative pools. The upper floor has a high-ceilinged living room with gas stove, dining room decorated with antique Indonesian wood carvings, kitchen, full bathroom, and bedroom with queen-size
neighborhood_overview: Restaurants in the Castro are always changing but we like Frances, Poesia, Firewood, Firefly (in Noe Valley), Osaka, Wasabi, Mama Ji's and Mekong Kitchen.  There is also an excellent Thai restaurant right around the corner.  There are lots of good short to long walks/hikes.  The famous Vulcan steps are a 10 minute walk away.
host_about: We live in San Francisco and spend time in New York as well.  We also have another place in Northern California in the country we spend time at.  I'm a private pilot and Paul is quite an accomplished ceramicist, though he does non-profit management consulting by profession. I run a retreat center ( (Website hidden by Airbnb) and am a computer consultant some of the time and real estate investor other times.  We have a cat who stays at our house here in San Francisco when we travel.  She is very, very affectionate and easy to care for.

neighborhood_overview: The melting pot of cultures, the murals, the restaurants, shops, farmer's market, walkability, festivals, bars, access to BART and MUNI.
host_about:
My wife and I have traveled the world, but have called San Francisco home for 25 years. We invite you to stay with us in our 1896 Edwardian home in the middle of the Mission District, San Francisco's oldest and arguably most vibrant neighborhood filled with a diverse range of some of the City's best restaurants, bars, parks, shops, and more. Not to mention our neighborhood is the warmest, flattest, and fog free part of San Francisco. 

We're 15 minutes from SFO by taxi, a block and a half from the 24th Bart Station and close to many bus and MUNI (subway) lines. Having visited Southeast Asia, Oceania, Australia, Europe, Central America, and of course all over North America, one theme holds true for all our adventures: discover the true culture and flavor wherever we are. 

As your host, we'll do everything we can to make sure you get off the beaten path. We're happy to share our favorite restaurants, local hangouts, and ensure you see the true San Francisco, not just the typical touristy sites. We're into everything from scuba diving, biking, kayaking, hiking, wine, art, music, food, festivals, museums, all things teens, parks, and more. Whatever you're into, we'll point you in the right direction so you have an authentic and memorable time in San Francisco. My motto is from the great Mahatma Ghandi: "Be the change you wish to see in the world." Our style of hosting reflects the needs of our guests. When possible, we like to meet our guests. However we understand that many of them are busy on a tight schedule or not interested to meet us so we respect that. We want to make sure every guest is comfortable and part of that is respecting boundaries and their personal space. 

We look forward to hosting you soon! If you have any questions, please feel free to ask. We're just a click away.

neighborhood_overview: Named for Mission Dolores founded in 1776, San FranciscoÃ¢â¬â¢s oldest neighborhood has some of its hottest new restaurants and galleries. neighborhoods all share a sunny outlook. Boasting some of the best weather in the city, the Mission District, takes advantage of an abundance of fog-free days. New restaurants and night spots are a draw while Mission Dolores, 16th and Dolores streets, is the oldest structure in San Francisco. Many of the cityÃ¢â¬â¢s pioneers are buried in an adjacent cemetery. The largest concentration of murals in the city adorn buildings, fences and walls throughout the district.
host_about:
I visited San Francisco many years ago as a tourist, and fell in love with the city.  
I told myself I'd come back, and I did!
I moved to San Francisco over 10 years ago, from the East Coast, for work.
During the winter, I'm up in Tahoe snowboarding almost every weekend.  The rest of the year I enjoy discovering new music and restaurants. When the wind is good, my latest hobby is sailing around the Bay with friends.  
I love to travel and try to do it as often as possible.
When I travel, I appreciate the hospitality of others and hope to return that hospitality when I have guests stay at my house.
I want you to feel welcomed and fall in love with San Francisco and Lake Tahoe, like I did.

-Mickey

name: Spacious Gem to Entertain or Relax
description:
Our home is a perfect spot for a family or group of friends visiting SF: equipped with an open-layout, modern kitchen/dining room; walking distance to a supermarket, drugstore, and Starbucks; and ample parking or easy access to public transportation.

The space
Our home is an immaculate Spanish style home with 1800 sq ft of finished space in charming Old Miraloma. Our 2-level corner property features lots of natural light, vaulted ceilings, parquet floors, recessed lighting, and views of Mt. Davidson. The eat-in Chef's kitchen includes stainless steel appliances, custom cabinets, slate tile floor, and a granite island and breakfast bar with large skylight. The dining area and living room with fireplace and flatscreen are also on the main level, along with a remodeled tile-and-marble bathroom with Jacuzzi and glass shower stall. Two bedrooms are on this same level, with one set up as a proper guestroom with Queen, and the other as a nursery (with crib). This bedro
neighborhood_overview: Miraloma Park is a residential neighborhood that has old San Francisco charm. (Our home was built in 1937, for example.) In our central location, you are close to the action but not in the action. Our home is a short bus ride or cab ride away from fun neighborhoods like the Castro and the Mission so you can go out to dinner and drinks but then return to a quiet refuge after a day of activities. It's close to public transportation which makes reaching downtown simple and quick. There is a shopping center with a grocery store, a sandwich shop, a burger joint, a pizza place, a drug store, and a Starbucks right behind our house. And if you want to experience nature there are many trails at Mt. Davidson and in Glen Canyon Park, both right in our 'hood, that are perfect for that morning jog or urban hike!
host_about:
I am a proud resident of the vibrant City by the Bay!  After growing up on the East Coast, I moved to SF in my early 20's, and here I am, 7 years later and still loving every moment here.  My husband Chris and I are now in our 30's, and as much as we enjoy our time in San Francisco, we spend many weekends visiting friends & family, skiing in Tahoe and traveling to new places.  We bought a beautiful home last year and want to join AirBnB so others can take advantage of our great place while we're away.

More about us...during the week, Chris is a high school teacher and I work at a hedge fund.  Our weekends in town often involve dance music, watching sporting events, and  doing activities like tennis and cycling to stay healthy together.  We love the big, fun network of energetic SF friends that always keeps us on our toes.  We are excited about the opportunity to meet new folks through airbnb and to help visitors have the best time ever while in SF.

Buena Vista Park is just a couple of blocks up the hill surrounded by amazing archictectural gems and breathtaking views of the city and the bay.  Duboce Park a block away is also surrounded by such quaint beautiful houses that they are on the tour bus route (those buses avoid our block because of our short  hill, keeping this section of our street a quiet secret!)  Yet with Haight St and Divisadero just a block away, public transportation, grocery stores, cafes and restaurants abound within a short walk.
host_about:
I came to San Francisco for the first time many years ago to visit my daughter.  I couldn't visit for long, sleeping in her and her roommate's living room. Time together was precious, hotels were too far and too expensive.  My dream of owning a house close to daughter and grandchildren came true.
  I am now  living the dream of hosting fellow visiting parents and grandparents, in addition to vacationers, business travelers,  individuals and families the world over.  I really enjoy sharing my house and my city.
My husband and I love family, friends, music, nature, great food and wine, old movies, sports.  We are hikers, birders and world travelers.  We appreciate cultural diversity and individual uniqueness.
My motto:  Dream it, love it, expect it, and you will experience it!

description:
Located in the heart of San Francisco atop beautiful Bernal Heights, our unique and colorful home offers a true San Francisco experience. Our Magical Garden retreat is a hidden oasis. Enjoy amazing Golden Gate Bridge and skyline vistas from any of our eight levels. Soak under the stars in our beautiful outdoor tub while marveling at the sparkling city lights. The summit of Bernal Hill is at our door for a hike or a run and offers a 360ÃÂ° vista of the city and unforgettable sunsets.

The space
DUE TO THE COVID 19 OUTBREAK WE ARE TAKING EXTRA CARE TO DISINFECT ALL SURFACES BETWEEN RESERVATIONS. WE GUARANTEE A HIGH LEVEL OF CLEANLINESS/DISINFECTION.

Our unique, eclectic home with it's Magical Garden serves as a sweet retreat in the heart of San Francisco. It would be perfect for business team building, as a yoga retreat, for a reunion, for a friends or family get together or just as a sanctuary to return to after a day of exploring our beautiful cit
neighborhood_overview:
Bernal Heights has some of the best weather in San Francisco. It also has the best views and has a safe, friendly village feel to it.

Our "main street" Cortland Avenue has a little of everything, including several world class restaurants.

Right outside our door is Bernal Hill, a beautiful piece of parkland that affords a 360ÃÂº view of San Francisco. If you are lucky you may see one of our local coyotes. Come here for sunrise, sunset or for star gazing!

Don't miss our Alemany Market which becomes a fabulous Farmers Market on Saturdays and a Flea Market on Sundays.
host_about:
Hi, I'm Jeannie.  My husband, Skate and I love to host guests in our beautiful home.  
 
We provide our guests with privacy while also offering travel and local recommendations based upon our 40+ years as San Franciscans.  We love meeting new people and making new friends.

Skate and I have travelled extensively throughout Europe, Asia, Middle East, Africa and North, Central and South America.  We love to explore back roads, back alleys and back woods. We can be exhausting to travel with! 

One of our favorite things to do is to travel simply by either camping or staying in local homes so that we get to really experience the culture and people of the region we are visiting.
 
We enjoy spending time in our garden and with our family, we also enjoy eating good food, traveling to new and exciting destinations, camping, sunshine and live music which you may hear Skate playing!
 
For us Airbnb is a wonderful way to travel but also through hosting a way to meet new people from all over the world while staying at home!

Skate and I look forward to meeting you!

name: Country living in the Mission!
description:
Our peaceful Mission District family home features three bedrooms, a fully equipped cook's kitchen, a big backyard with chickens and a trampoline, and is situated in the middle of a neighborhood full of amazing food and charming coffee shops.

We take cleaning and health concerns very seriously and will leave supplies for guests, including hand sanitizer, alcohol spray and sanitizing cleaners.

The space
Beautiful, peaceful country home in the middle of the city! A great house for families, our Mission District home is a 100-year old Queen Anne Victorian with three bedroom areas. Space includes:
* Master bedroom - 1 queen bed
* Second bedroom - 1 queen + 1 twin very thick futon that can be put out on the floor. Note: this room has a giant skylight in the ceiling and as such no shade - it can get very bright in the mornings.
* Third bedroom - 1 full/double bed, opens onto 3rd floor deck overlooking backyard
Office/art room
Living
host_about:
Pete and Jen have lived in the Mission since the early 1990s, and have lived in this house for nearly 30 years. We have a small family (two daughters 19 & 15) and together have tried to create a special, peaceful home that evokes country-life as much as possible in an urban setting - evidenced by our love of chickens and edible plants. 

Jen co-directs an immigrant rights nonprofit organization that promotes humansrights and social justice. Pete works in a leadership role on climate and energy policy for the state of California.

neighborhood_overview:
THE NEIGHBORHOOD

The Inner Richmond is one of the most popular, convenient neighborhoods in San Francisco:
- Three blocks from Golden Gate Park, specifically near Conservatory of Flowers, The California Academy of Sciences, De Young Museum, Japanese Gardens, and Botanical Gardens.
- Three blocks from Clement Street, including its fabulous restaurants (such as Burma Superstar, B Star, Richmond Republic, Giorgio's Pizza, Toy Boat Dessert), many coffee shops, See's Candies, bakeries, Green Apple Bookstore (regularly voted best used bookstore in SF), spas, and more.
- The Inner Richmond is home to the "other" or "real" Chinatown: less touristy than downtown, amazing food (restaurants and Asian supermarkets), fun shops.
- Six blocks from USF's huge and beautiful Koret Health and Recreation Center, for all your exercise needs.
- Five blocks from the Presidio, where you can experience breath-taking views, hikes, golf, and, of course, the Golden Gate
host_about:
We are a married couple, with two children.  We have traveled the world and were particularly grateful for the generosity of many hosts who opened up their homes to us, often demonstrating their desire for us to love and enjoy their city and country. Our hopes, at that time, was that one day, we would own our own home, and meet and host visitors from all over. 

In 2011, we moved from NYC to San Francisco.  We bought our dream home in September, 2012.  We enjoy playing host and welcoming visitors into our home and suggesting great places to visit while staying in the San Francisco area.

We love partner dancing, especially lindy hop.

neighborhood_overview:
LOCATION:
--The main entrance to Golden Gate Park is just a couple blocks away. So, very easy to walk to the California Academy of Sciences, DeYoung Museum, Japanese Tea Gardens, Botanical Gardens, Arboretum, Carousel, and a couple of different playgrounds.
--Tons of great restaurants, coffee shops, crepe places, nail salons, book stores, and cute shops and clothing boutiques within a couple of blocks. One of local restaurants was recently featured on Diners, Drive-ins and Dives. Our neighborhood is considered a destination neighborhood for great restaurants and bakeries.
--Ocean Beach is just 2.5 miles away. Easy run/walk to the beach. Or take the N-judah train and be there in 10 minutes.
--Take the train in the opposite direction and you can be downtown in 15 minutes. The train goes all the way to the Giants AT&T ball park. Great way to go see a game!
--UCSF is a few blocks away. It has a great fitness center/gym and swimming pool.
--Several
host_about:
I love to travel and fell in love with San Francisco on a trip and just had to move here!  I'm so happy and proud to be a San Franciscan!  I love sharing the city's beautiful landscape, neighborhoods and culture with first-time visitors and long-term residents alike.  

My family and I own several apartments that we have restored with love and care.  Our furnished apartments are always rented out long-term.  When we have a short gap between renters, we occasionally are able to offer a unit on Airbnb.  Sometimes, it's even a way to find great tenants--especially for those that like to "try before they buy."  

There are lots of great and useful ways to use Airbnb to help San Francisco's new, existing and future residents.  My goal is to insure guests have an excellent and authentic SF experience, and that they discover a few reasons that they might want to call SF home!

Guest access
You will have access to the top part of the house, the shared back yard and the drive w
neighborhood_overview:
Sunnyside is on the South West side of the city. Not far from the ocean so the weather can be cool and foggy. We are a 10 min. drive (longer on the bus 20 min.) to Ocean Beach, the zoo, Stern Grove, Lake Merced, Golden Gate Park, San Francisco Sate University, City College, Mt. Davidson, and more.

San Francisco is jam packed with places to explore, all within a bus ride or short drive.

The neighborhood is very quiet and neighbors are friendly. It is located near Ocean Ave. which has a Whole Foods and other shops and restaurants. There is a Safeway two blocks away on Monterrey Blvd. The other two neighborhoods that are close by are West Portal and Glen Park. There are two BART stations nearby - one at Glen Park and one at Balboa Station. There is a bus (the number 43) that goes from the corner of our street all the way across town. There is also a bus (number 23) on Monterrey that goes to the beach and zoo.
host_about: We are a recently retired couple looking forward to our free time and being able to travel again.  Serge is from France and we visit family there once a year.  We are also hoping to spend time with our daughter and grandson in Michigan where Nancy is originally from.  We have lived in San Francisco for over 40 years and consider it home.  There is so much to explore and discover in the area and in California and the West!  We are happy to share our home while we come and go from our travels.  We hope that you will care for our home as we do and enjoy your time while here.

See below for information about our rigorous cleaning and disinfecting protocol.

The space
Our lovely Queen Anne home dates from 1890, though its grown in size and sophistication over the years, as has the neighborhood. It's located on a quiet, treelined little street, one lane, one-way and only one block long, but within steps of everything one could want: many different bus and metro lines, "The Wiggle" bike route, bars, cafes, stores, and Duboce Park, one of San Francisco's best. On Walk Score it rates 100 as both a "Walker's Paradise" and a "Rider's Paradise"; it's also rated 89 for cycling as "Very Bikeable (some hills, excellent lanes)".

name: Charming Cottage with Bay View
description:
The space
Charming, beautiful cozy home (800 sq. ft/75 qm) located right above Candlestick Park with beautiful garden and great view of San Francisco Bay. Internet included. 2 bedrooms, the downstairs room has French doors that open onto the garden. From the upstairs bedroom you can see the sun rise over the water and East Bay hills. The garden contains many beautiful flowers, around 10 lemon trees that produce fruit all year round. In September the plum trees will have a lot of fruit and the Pippin Apple tree will have a million apples on it (great for pie). Full kitchen (I love to cook). Full laundry down stairs. Bathroom has a shower (no bath tub). Plenty of parking and super neighbors. Shirley & Earl will chat you up. Shirley will probably come over and pick plums to make jam. If you're nice, Josh & Ray will invite you to dinner.

The neighborhood is quiet. Cafe's, bars & restaurants in the Mission are 10 minutes away, downtown is 5 minutes more by car. The

neighborhood_overview:
THE NEIGHBORHOOD

The Inner Richmond is one of the most popular, convenient neighborhoods in San Francisco:
- Three blocks from Golden Gate Park, specifically near Conservatory of Flowers, The California Academy of Sciences, De Young Museum, Japanese Gardens, and Botanical Gardens.
- Three blocks from Clement Street, including its fabulous restaurants (such as Burma Superstar, B Star, Richmond Republic, Giorgio's Pizza, Toy Boat Dessert), many coffee shops, See's Candies, bakeries, Green Apple Bookstore (regularly voted best used bookstore in SF), spas, and more.
- The Inner Richmond is home to the "other" or "real" Chinatown: less touristy than downtown, amazing food (restaurants and Asian supermarkets), fun shops.
- Six blocks from USF's huge and beautiful Koret Health and Recreation Center, for all your exercise needs.
- Five blocks from the Presidio, where you can experience breath-taking views, hikes, golf, and, of course, the Golden Gate Bridge
host_about:
We are a married couple, with two children.  We have traveled the world and were particularly grateful for the generosity of many hosts who opened up their homes to us, often demonstrating their desire for us to love and enjoy their city and country. Our hopes, at that time, was that one day, we would own our own home, and meet and host visitors from all over. 

In 2011, we moved from NYC to San Francisco.  We bought our dream home in September, 2012.  We enjoy playing host and welcoming visitors into our home and suggesting great places to visit while staying in the San Francisco area.

We love partner dancing, especially lindy hop.

The space

The house is quiet and light-filled from many skylights, and boasts views of Noe Valley and a sliver of downtown San Francisco and the Bay. neighborhood_overview:
Noe Valley is a primarily residential neighborhood, although there are two bustling commercial strips: the first along 24th Street, between Church Street and Diamond Street, and the second, less dense corridor along Church Street, between 24th Street and 30th Street.

Ruth Asawa was a resident of Noe Valley from 1962 until her death in August of 2013. Carlos Santana graduated from James Lick Middle School on Noe Street in the early 1960s, as did Benjamin Bratt in the following decade. Medea Benjamin also lives in the neighborhood. Famous residents include Scott Hutchins, Evan Williams and Mark Zuckerberg.
host_about:
Hi, I'm Alex! I'm an Italian-born German-speaking US resident with dreams of being a New Zealand farmer.  Since I started hosting in 2011, Airbnb has become a big part of my life. I am thrilled to have been a Host Educators at the Open in Paris in 2015 and honored to be asked back to be presenters at the 2016 Open in LA. I also started a company, Properly, to help hosts like myself convey turnover instructions to our helpers through a visual checklist app. It also provides a way for hosts to share,  find and train cleaners in their area. 

Running a start up company is time consuming, but when I have down time, I love spending time in the outdoors, I am an avid  cyclist, kayaker and hiker.  I can't resist a gadget and my wife Evelyn and I love hosting dinner parties of all sizes - whether in a geodesic dome at Burning Man,  or in our home in Noe Valley.  I love traveling and I have called San Francisco home for over 20 years and love it.

host_about:
I manage the house with Lita my 21 year old daughter & her father Fred. Having our house on Airbnb is helping us with our daughters college fund. She graduated from High School in 2019 & has taken a gap & COVID year before deciding on a university & country that she wants to go to school in. 

Renting our home also funded a new garden apartment that will be for a long term tenant.

Airbnb also helped fund 'Tartlet Bar',  a food business Wendy had with her families farm.

We own the house together, but split our time there with Lita our daughter. We co-parent & raised our daughter in whatÃ¢â¬â¢s called a Ã¢â¬ÅnestingÃ¢â¬Â situation. One of us are usually in town & available if you need anything.

We have lived in San Francisco since 1989, we get out of the city as much as possible, but always seem to return.

Wendy is a creative consultant & avid paddle boarder. She speaks French, English, understands Spanish & is learning Portuguese. She's currently a digital nomad making her way around the continents. One of her passions is to see the world and study different cultures, which she has done extensively (she wants to be an anthropologist when she grows up ;.). 

We believe the world is Lita's education, with 3 languages and several countries already under her belt she is a gypsy at heart. SheÃ¢â¬â¢s fluent in French, Spanish, English, & is teaching herself Japanese. She took 2019/2020 to explore Europe & work in Japan before she attends a University in 2022.

Fred is French, fluent in French, English & Spanish, a photographer, entrepreneur, surfer, world traveler and owns two small business in SF; Dalva (a bar in the mission district) and Grenouille-French Vintage Antiques.

We're also doing Airbnb because we like the idea of meeting like minded travelers, people who seek adventure, people who believe we can learn from everyone we meet and enjoy absorbing other cultures as much as we do. Is it possible to be part of a community while being a gypsy and a nomad? So far it's working out to be yes...

host_about:
I'm a Southerner by birth (born in NC, grew up in Memphis) but have been in San Francisco and working in Silicon Valley for over 20 years. My husband, Nick, is a OB/GYN. He's off to Budapest for a year because he was recently awarded a Fulbright to study home birth in Hungary and Prezi is headquartered there. I'll be visiting him frequently, so why not.  

To be honest, we're a little nervous about renting out our home, because it is just that: our home. Two renovations and twenty years of futzing and we've got it exactly where we want it--to live and to retire. Fortunately, all remodeling choices were to made with the goal of sharing our home with our family and friends. I guess now we're just extending that circle a little further. 

Other socially relevant deets: I grew up in Memphis (high school: MUS), went to NCSU undergrad and MIT for business school.  In between I danced/acted in NYC (stage, not clubs. Well, both). I'm also an author of two business books and two novels (see Amazon).

Nick (Rubashkin) grew up in Maine and went to Brandeis for undergrad and Stanford for medical school. He did is residency at UCSF and practiced for 5 years at St. Lukes before receiving this Fulbright. He is also a published author of an anthology of Medical Students' personal stories (again, Amazon).

host_about:
We love keeping active, body, mind and soul.  Jim retired as director of a senior citizens center, and Louise retired as an English and creative writing professor at the local community college. She now teaches small memoir workshops and Jim taught history classes for while and is now doing a history of his family as well as house projects and walks.
 Louise writes and is working on her fifth book. We both love to interact with people of all ages and we are tolerant and open people. Jim  loves to read and keep up with the news and seeing art. We both love reading both fiction and non-fiction,  visiting museums, watching movies, seeing plays, visiting with family and friends and experiencing the great outdoors. We love meeting new people from all around the world. We travel back East once a year to visit family, and Louise recently taught a workshop in St. Thomas where her sister lives. We love to travel in California, as well. Louise went to the U. of Wisconsin and keeps up with college friends and she and Jim both attended the University of Buffalo. We visit Buffalo where Jim grew up and New York City where Louise grew up! We also have grandchildren in Connecticut so love to visit the East Coast.
We also still love the outdoors.  We love art and books and music.  We're also both independent people and understand and respect the need for privacy!

Bret Harte is a multicultural neighborhood, with a rich history in San Francisco's jazz scene, and is considered to be a bit quieter than the SOMA and Mission neighborhoods, yet much closer to the downtown area than the Richmond or Sunset districts.

The property is conveniently located on the side south of the city (which is particularly useful for those commuting to the Peninsula, South Bay, or South San Francisco Area), and is connected to downtown San Francisco via a direct Muni train.

neighborhood_overview: The Mission is a vibrant mix of cultures,  famous for its many murals, creativity and walkability. neighborhood_overview: The Sunset is a unique demographic of surfers, dog lovers, and beach-goers. Typically the Sunset is foggy for June and July, but is clear most other days of the year.  Typical yearly temperatures hover in the 60-65 degrees Fahrenheit.  Our neighborhood is a friendly community, where most of us know each other by name and many natives still live in the area. The sunset district is like the "suburbs of the City", making it a more relaxed environment with all the benefits of a big city and entertainment at your fingertips.  Golden Gate Park (GGP) is within walking distance (1 mile) and holds the Outside Lands concert and the Hardly Strictly Bluegrass Festival. GGP also has the Academy of Science museum, De Young art museum, and Japanese Tea Garden. The Great Highway offers a beautiful 5 mile walking path from Sloat ave. to the Cliff House/Sutro Baths.  It is great for running, biking, walking. Popular restaurants include: Thanh Long, Outerlands, Cliff House, Beach Chalet & Brewery, Celia'
host_about: We are native San Franciscans, work full time, enjoy the outdoors, camping, the beach, and enjoy wine with friends and family. I am particularly clean and love a comfortable home to relax in.  With roots from Hawaii, we try to live by the spirit of Aloha and the virtue of being honest and genuine with others.  We have traveled to exotic places around the world, including Bali, Costa Rica, Europe, Canada, Mexico, Japan and have visited over 20 U.S. states.  We love meeting new people and sharing our city life. Our lives are revolved around our children and raising a stable family in this fast paced city.  We frequent Lake Tahoe for skiing and snowboarding and Hawaii in the summer to visit family. Ocean beach is our front yard and is our haven for an extra breath. Constantly learning how to simplify and enjoy life is a focus.

neighborhood_overview:
The inner Mission, from 16th to 24th Street and spanning Dolores, Guerrero, Valencia, and Mission Street, has thrift to high end stores, dive bars to gourmet restaurants, coffeehouses, taquerias, galleries and an avant-garde theater. The Valencia Corridor is a foodie haven. It has been written up by The New York Times, Food & Wine Magazine, and other publications for it's restaurants.

The Mission neighborhood is popular for its eclectic mix of people, vintage stores, shopping, dining, it's walk-ability and mural tours, night life and for being the sunniest neighborhood in San Francisco.

Nestled next to the Mission, Noe Valley has become a quaint, family-oriented neighborhood, with good shopping and great dining options.

The Castro is one of San Francisco's most vibrant communities, saturated with popular bars and top restaurants, as well as home to the Castro Theatre.

neighborhood_overview:
Dogpatch is a registered State Historical District steeped in rich San Francisco history. Old timers say it got it's name from the wild dogs that used to roam around back when there were meat processing plants in the area. Dogpatch is also one of the newest neighborhoods in terms of development and now abounds with many excellent restaurants,bars,shops, galleries,museums, and of course high tech business. There are several gyms nearby as well as numerous yoga studios and a rock climbing facility. Take a run or walk along the SF waterfront and the new Crane Cove Park, (five minute walk from house) , to the famous Ferry Building and Farmers Market or Oracle Ball Park. The UCSF Mission Bay biotech research center and the UCSF WomenÃ¢â¬â¢s and ChildrenÃ¢â¬â¢s hospital are a short 2 block walk from our house.
Short 5 minute walk to Muni and Caltrain.

neighborhood_overview:
This area is called "Little Hollywood." Local legend is that Mae West had a hideaway bungalow at the end of the street. There are cute, craftsmen's houses along the block. The neighbors are super nice!

The neighborhood is called Little Hollwood. It's a residential area so there's not a lot of shops or cafes to walk to, but there are a few, and more restaurants and shops 5 mins drive away. It's very close to the 2nd largest park in San Francisco, John Mclaren park, which is lovely for picnics, hiking, duck pond, amphitheater, amazing city and mountain views. It's also close to the Candlestick recreation point with great walking trails along the bay and beautiful city views. The San Bruno mountains are also nearby and offer great hiking trails.

neighborhood_overview:
The "outerlands" as this area of the city used to be called is where nature meets urban, widely and wonderfully. Families, surfers, artists, hipsters, techies and eccentrics come together to create a multicultural neighborhood that is dominated by the ocean and the sky!
Really I think the Sunset District is San Francisco's best kept secret. It is clean and safe and quiet at night. You are about a half hour from the hustle and bustle of downtown (by car or public transport). Out here the streets are wider, the backyards bigger, and free parking is easy to find. People who like the outdoors love the location, especially for surfing, jogging, cycling, and hiking.
Typically the Sunset can be foggy in June and July, but is clear and beautiful most of the rest of the year. Fall is stellar. Yearly temperatures hover in the 60-65 degrees. host_about:
Hello and thank you for showing interest in my home. I'm an interiors and product designer and my home is ever changing and evolving in colors and style.....I like to change things up! Hopefully I've kept the photos current so you won't be surprised when you arrive! I live here here with my two children, Scarlett 13 and Romeo 10....and we have a lovely dog, Loulou, that we share with friends in the neighborhood. We love (Website hidden by Airbnb) family friendly, lot's of kids and dogs, a great local store, coffee shop and fabulous community which has been strengthened even more since March 16th.

Wow, these are interesting time we are living in these days! 

Just like you, I'm looking to escape my home for the holidays and, just like you, I'm concerned about taking my family somewhere just in case it's not 100% safe, clean etc. 

We've all learned a lot about cleanliness over the past couple of months and let me tell you that I'm taking my home cleaning routine on the road with me where ever it is I go! 

Airbnb has been kind enough to send all hosts a recommended cleaning routine and I've been using this at home on a weekly basis. Most of it I was already doing....using disinfectant wipes to clean light switches, door handles, appliances (Website hidden by Airbnb) know that my house is super clean! I will be supplying you with your own batch of disinfectant wipes all over the house just in case you want to be extra safe. I know I would want that!

All guest linens and pillows, duvets etc. are separate from my own, all mattresses have covers too so you can rest assured that there will been cross over from my family to yours.

Feel free to connect, ask questions, voice concerns.....I'm happy to make your stay as comfortable as possible.

Enjoy the San Francisco lifestyle in this fabulous and light-filled 3 bedroom, 2-1/2 bath home with two beautiful home offices and an enchanting and South-facing private garden. The house was built in 1906 and fully restored by the owners, an American architect and an Italian garden designer. Detached on three sides, the house offers ample sunlight and garden views from every room.
This is a perfect family house with all bedrooms on the second floor and home office spaces on each level. This beautiful, cozy and well-located home is the perfect nesting place for a couple or family that enjoys living in a thoughtfully designed environment. High ceilings, radiant floor heating, parking with electric charger, outdoor decks, and original detailing appoint the home. Across the street is a lovely cafe and Holly Park, St. Mary's Park and Cortland Ave are steps away. Minutes away from 280/101 for easy access to downtown, SFO and the peninsula.

Gue

But I feel especially lucky that we ended up in Noe Valley. It truly is an amazing neighborhood!

After retiring from a full time teaching career I have provided regular,  part time child care for my adorable grandkids, taken lots of art classes and traveled. host_about:
My husband and I have been together for 11 years and have traveled to the corners of the country and beyond. Ryan spent some time growing up in the Bay Area and we returned to SF in 2013.

Being avid travelers who frequently used hotels and tried a different homesharing site, those experiences did not compare to the TLC we received when staying with family and friends. We realized that adding little touches like family artwork, a welcome kit with snacks, wine, fresh flowers from our yard (when in season) and a stockpile of toiletries in case anything didn't make its way into your suitcase, makes an ordinary place to lay your head a welcoming retreat.

We are both college-educated professionals. We enjoy finding local restaurants, making fun meals at home, exploring our city, and working in the yard.

As a same-sex couple, we understand the need for inclusive accommodations when we travel. We promote an inclusive environment for guests regardless of race, color, religion, gender, gender identity or expression, sexual orientation, national origin, genetics, disability, or age. 

When we're traveling, Ryan is usually looking for great running routes and I'm looking for great golf courses to play. Together, we seek out delicious local restaurants, warm beaches, and activities that give us a greater sense of local culture.

Thanks for checking out our profile and we look forward to welcoming you to San Francisco or seeing you wherever our travels take us!

Ashbury Heights is an upscale neighborhood with grand homes situated up the hill from the Haight-Ashbury historic district and Golden Gate Park. A short stroll down the hill, offers: The California Academy Of Sciences, the DeYoung Museum, Japanese Tea Garden, Botanical Garden at Strybing Arboretum and much more.

The Historic Haight neighborhood is a short walk, with great people watching, eateries, vintage clothing boutiques, and pubs.

The vibrant Castro neighborhood is a walk down the hill, with restaurants, shops, and bars.

Eating and drinking: Bacon Bacon, La Boulangerie de San Francisco, Kamekyo Sushi, Kezar Pub, Padrecito, Magnolia, Alembic, Sparrow Bar and Kitchen, The Pork Store and so much more! Groceries: Haight Market.

host_about:
Hi there,
I am a healer, working with Hospice. I am inspired to drink life up, understanding that there is a finite amount of life to be had. I love to travel. My last amazing journey was to the Amazon. Even more memorable than the visual aspects of that trip were the auditory surprises. In addition to the contant vibrational buzzing and hissing in the air, I have 2 words for you, especially if you get to the Amazon: "Howler Monkeys". They truly sound like I imagine dinosaurs would sound. Apparently they get such volume and monster howl from a hole in a bone in their throats. Must be heard to be believed. But I digress! I'm a weekly dancer, pulling out the boots for two step, the retro wear for East Coast swing, and I waltz every chance I get no matter what I'm wearing. I love beautiful found objects. I write poetry and short stories. I have a private psychotherapy practice and teach mindfulness to people who are interested in more resiliency, more ZEST!  But I bet if you talked to my friends, they'd note the overall goofy, delighted way I like to carry on with life in general. As Helen Keller said, "Life is a banquet, but most of us are starving to death." So I invite you to come to my home and take a big bite out of life. The time is now.

host_about:
Hello, my name is Jose. I welcome you to our Airbnb site and hopefully also to my place in beautiful San Francisco.

I am fortunate to work with a few good friends or family members who acts as my co-hosts who are very easy-going, friendly, responsible and organized. We are professionals in high tech, business, and education; During the first two months of this new year, I will be your primary point of contact and host. But with a Ã¢â¬ÅwingmanÃ¢â¬Â nearby ready to offer me and you support as needed.

I have been hosting Airbnb since 2015. It has been a great journey. I have had the chance to meet new people from around the world, to hear their journey, and to share with them our beloved city San Francisco.

Nothing pleases me more than seeing guests who have enjoyed my home and our city of San Francisco, one of the most beautiful in the world. We are not perfect but we strive to be. 

Take care. 

Jose

name: Mission Victorian with Hot Tub and Parking
description:
Our elegant 3-bedroom Victorian flat on a bright tree-lined street in the Inner Mission has a front yard deck, an idyllic backyard garden with hot tub and chic changing cabana and garage parking for one car. It's within close walking distance of BART/buses, restaurants, bars, and nightclubs.

The space
Our flat is on the bottom floor of a historic two-story Victorian built in 1889. The building has high ceilings, period details, lots of natural light, hardwood floors, a newly remodeled kitchen and one bathroom. There is garage parking for one car.

The space consists of a large living room, formal dining room, eat-in chefs kitchen with a darling vintage booth, and three cozy bedrooms: two queen sized beds, and one single. There is also the option of having 2 additional guests sleep on a queen sized sofa bed in the living room.

Sit on the front deck in the morning sunshine and watch the neighborhood come alive. Our quiet tree-lined street is c
neighborhood_overview:
Located in the hip Mission district, this area is vibrant with history and culture. The Mission brings together all of the facets of diverse urban living.
It has the best weather in SF; it will be bright and sunny here and foggy all over town.
Parks dot the landscape: Bernal Hill, Precita and Dolores are within walking distance
Both high-end and budget eating options exist nearby
Bars and nightclubs hosting live music and DJs
Other fun neighborhoods (Haight, Castro, SOMA) are a short bus or cab/Lyft ride away
Quaint bookstores and boutiques

San Francisco's most eclectic mix of shops line nearby Valencia Street.

name: Classic Elegance Pacific Heights
description:
This grand 1908 home is the epitome of sophistication, close to The Presidio, Fillmore, and Laurel Village shops and restaurants. It is filled with classic details and luxury amenities, two gardens, and fabulous cooking and entertaining spaces. It is ideal for corporate team-building, adult family gatherings, and deluxe getaways with friends.

The space
This is an historic 1908 home in the Mediterranean style, designed by Carl Mueseldorffer, a noted SF architect. It was the home of Senator Dianne Feinstein when she was Mayor of San Francisco, and was featured in Architectural Digest when it was owned by noted interior designer Suzanne Tucker. It is made of wood, smoking, vaping, and candles are not allowed in the house! Rooms have high ceilings and lovely molding and detailing. It is filled with books, which you are welcome to peruse. It is designed to be warm and inviting, but still refined. We hope you enjoy the space as much as we have.

When the hous
neighborhood_overview:
Pacific Heights offers the best of San Francisco living. The Presidio is just a few blocks away -- go to the Starbuck's next to Lucasfilm and see the Yoda statue in front of the building. On Sundays there is an "Off the Grid" food truck gathering from 11-3 -- a great way to sample a number of specialties. Then walk it off along Crissy Field beach, with incomparable views of the Golden Gate Bridge and Alcatraz.
If you amble down Sacramento Street to the right you will reach charming Laurel Village, with upscale family shops, restaurants, and services. If you walk left you will come to Divisadero -- don't miss B Patisserie on California just before Divisadero -- pastries to die for, and lovely sandwiches across the street at B on the Go. Keep going four more blocks and you'll be on tony Fillmore Street, home to some of the chicest shops in SF. Great upscale Indian food at Dosa, Italian at SPQR and Pizzeria Delfina, and liquid nitrogen ice cream at Smitten. Stroll Union Street for
host_about:
I am a writer with far-flung interests and a penchant for people. I am the author of books and articles on style, art and travel. I also write corporate financial reports and marketing materials, which reflects my previous career managing a service-oriented healthcare business for seniors. I also serve as a board member of nonprofit organizations; the fabric of our communities is much stronger when everyone has an opportunity to succeed. 

I love to make people comfortable; this home reflects that, along with a desire for functionality, luxury and beauty. I am fortunate to live in one of the most magical places in the world. Sharing this home ensures that more people are able to appreciate this vibrant, diverse, and delightful City by the Bay.

name: 3 BR Home by the Beach with Sunset Ocean Views
description:
Enjoy our entire comfortable home, with romantic sunset ocean views from your private deck! Cook in our fully stocked kitchen, and explore the excellent local cafes, restaurants markets and bars. Family friendly. Walk to the beach, zoo, grocery, dining, trains and buses. Parking on our street is easy, for SF, and free. Borrow beach stuff, including chairs, 2 boogie boards and a surf board. 3 friendly and loving sister-cats come with our home. Caring for them is part of the package.

The space
This is our family home, available only a few times a year. Six sleep comfortably in beds, plus there's a short couch, settee and chaise.

The master bedroom is peaceful and romantic, with a sunset ocean view, ensuite bath, King pillow-top bed and a large private deck.

The home's second bedroom is the biggest in the house. It has a firm new Queen bed, lots of closet space, and toys, furniture and books suitable for teenagers and younger children as well.
neighborhood_overview:
We are in the Sunset district: a residential neighborhood with attached family homes, schools, restaurants and shops. The beach and zoo are only an 8-minute walk away. There are Thai, pizza, and excellent Chinese restaurants within a few blocks. A grocery store, park and playground are even closer.

The neighborhood is a bit up-and-coming, and scattered throughout are some arguably-best-in-the-city gems including a bakery, brewery, urban clothing company, surf shop and a number of restaurants. neighborhood_overview:
Bernal Heights is one of the last non-gentrified neighborhoods in San Francisco. It is safe and easy to navigate, with a playground, library, grocery store, and a variety of restaurants, all within walking distance of the house.

Bernal is built into a hill. Our house is on the southern slope. A half mile walk uphill will take you to the trails around the top of the hill from where you get a spectacular view of the city.

Bernal's north slope has been referred to as one of San Francisco's "banana belts", with warmer temperatures from San Francisco Bay and less marine fog making its way inland.

neighborhood_overview: Besides having the most reliably sunny weather, the Mission District is one of the most rich and diverse neighborhoods in San Francisco, and interest and excitement can be found on almost any street corner.  Whether your desire is to take in the parks, colorful murals and authentic taco shops, or to sample from the many boutiques, cocktail bars and upscale restaurants, the Mission District has something for every taste and imagination.
host_about:
A San Francisco native (my first day care was just five blocks from where I am now), I lived in San Diego for college and New York City for graduate school.  After working big corporate jobs in New York for five years, and then in San Francisco for three after moving back, I decided to try to go out on my own, and build a small business and consulting practice.

To help with income as I got started, I decided to rent two spare bedrooms in my home.  But even as my business has grown, I've found that the enjoyment and excitement of hosting travelers from around the world -- in a house that I love, and in the neighborhood that continues to awe me -- has been something I've wanted to continue.  For it brings me great pleasure to open up my house to visitors and share with them all that I marvel at in SF.

A foodie, and an outdoor enthusiast, I'd be delighted to share with you my favorite restaurants and hiking spots (and as a volunteer guide at Muir Woods, I could regale you with redwood facts for an hour), or to assist with your trip planning in any other way that I can.  

I hope that I can help you have a perfect trip, and that you get to enjoy Casa de Virgil, the Mission District, and San Francisco as much as I do!

neighborhood_overview:
Our home is located in the Haight-Ashbury neighborhood, the geographic center of San Francisco. The Haight is best known as the origin of the 1960's counter-culture, hippies, and the "Summer Of Love". Colorful, scraggly characters still roam Haight Street and vintage clothing shops abound.

Haight street is lined with restaurants, cafes, and great shops. We have three organic grocery markets, including Whole Foods within a five-block walk and a weekly farmers market!

We are right at the Panhandle, just two blocks from Golden Gate Park Park. This huge, beautiful park boasts lakes, fields, an arboretum, a Japanese tea garden, the Conservatory of Flowers, the DeYoung Museum, and the California Academy of Sciences -- the greenest museum in the world, with a living roof, planetarium and tropical rainforest canopy! The park ends at the Pacific Ocean, 4 serene miles from our home. Watch surfers brave the waves of Ocean Beach.

Explore gorgeous San Francisc

neighborhood_overview:
The Bayview is a sunny and up-and-coming (transitional/not fully gentrified) neighborhood that is primarily residential (families with kids). It is only a 20 minute drive to most tourist attractions or a 40 minute direct MUNI (light rail) ride to downtown. Winner of the 2015 SF Curbed Best Neighborhood Award which commended Bayview for its community gardens and growing arts/food/beverage scene.

*MULTI-CULTURAL AND SOCIO-ECONOMIC DIVERSITY*

Bayview is uniquely diverse in that it is both a multi-cultural and a socio-economically blended area. This is truly one of the only areas in the city where you will find African-American, Latino, Asian, and white families of all different economic classes living next door to each other. Because the neighborhood also has a large immigrant population, you will hear people talking to one another in Spanish, Chinese, and other languages. Neighbors are friendly with one another, so don't be surprised if people wave or say hello or

neighborhood_overview: Cole Valley is just a few minutes walk  from Golden Gate Park, so you can easily visit everything the park has to offer. In addition, our street accesses several miles of hiking trails in a greenspace protected Eucalyptus forrest.  The DeYoung Museum, Conservatory of Flowers, California Academy of Science, as well as the Japanese Tea Garden are all in Golden Gate Park and very nearby.  Kezar Stadium (original home to the 49ers) is at the end of our street if you would like to run some laps or stairs. I regularly deep clean the house with Magic Erasers to help keep th
neighborhood_overview:
The Outer Sunset/Parkside district is very suburban in feel yet more urban in that most suburban neighborhoods. We have several fun streets that provide city night life like Taraval Street, Noreiga Street, Judah Street, and Irving Street. Those are our streets to go for restaurants, night life, sports bars, and most all market and merchant needs.

Two blocks up from my house North is Noreiga Street which has several authentic Cantonese Chinese food and is regularly filled. Noreiga Teriyaki has very good sushi. It's a great street to buy discount groceries and explore trying new foods from Canton province.

On weekends you can enjoy the Outer Sunset Merchantile and Farmer's Market that lines 37th Avenue West of Sunset Blvd, North of St. Ignatius High School. It's a fun place to stroll, shop and connect with locals.
host_about:
I joined Airbnb in May 2016 but delayed hosting until the house was finished being renovated.  I'll start hosting starting in August 2017.  I live downstairs and will be available most weekdays M-F before 2pm.  I'm a third generation native San Franciscan on both sides of my family, i.e my grandparents, great grandparents and my parents on both sides grew up here or lived here for many years after immigrating here from Finland, Iceland, Wales and Chile.  While I have a strong lineage here, there's always more to learn about SF.  

I'm hospitable and quiet. A student and I work full time.  I love dogs, cats and parakeets, traveling to Hawaii, New York and Europe, love nature and outdoor sports, classic films, non-fiction literature, mysteries and all food.

As a guest I'm quiet and respectful.  As a host I'm considerate and attentive.  I will accommodate to my guests preference for privacy or communicative interests. 

When I travel I look for authenticity rather than tourist traps.  Trying different foods is a great way of experiencing different cultures.  

As a host, I'm interested in hosting travelers/visitors in my home in the Outer Sunset/Parkside District of SF. I'm two blocks from a Safeway Grocery store, one block from the #48 bus and four blocks from the L Taraval MUNI metro streetcar that goes to downtown SF.  I prefer to host reliable and responsible people with solid references and a good history of positive experiences using Airbnb.com.  

I'd say my home is ideal for hosting families with kids as well as couples and students either for a long weekend getaway or a two week vacation or longer.  I live in a safe, extremely quiet neighborhood with plenty of free parking and kid-friendly activities nearby such as the Zoo, Golden Gate Park,  Stonestown Mall, Ocean Beach and Lake Merced where kayaking, bicycling and golfing abound.  Dressing in layers is key to keep up with weather changes.

I look forward to meeting you and hope your stay at my home will be relaxing and make you feel welcomed.

Our Central Richmond Neighborhood incorporates the best of the City. Our quiet tree-lined street is family oriented and close knit. You will see kids playing in front of their homes, tons of dogs enjoying their walks, and lots of friendly people who will always say hello. Just a few blocks away you will find the major commercial Clement & Geary corridor, packed with restaurants, shops, cafes, pharmacies, boutiques, gift shops, service/repair shops, dry cleaners, grocery stores ... and more. We have a great Farmers Market on Sunday mornings with live music and lots of produce, meats, baked goods, flowers and yummy things to eat while you shop.

I would love to share info on all my favorite places in the city and give you suggestions based on your interests.

name: Gorgeous Victorian with Views, Near Mission
description:
Sunny, dramatic Victorian house with 3 bedrooms, 2 baths, gourmet kitchen with eating bar for 5, + dining room w/table for 8. Living room with spectacular view of Twin Peaks plus family room with comfy couch and TV. 1 bedroom and bath on main floor, two bedrooms and a full bath upstairs with stunning views of downtown, Bay Bridge and Twin Peaks. Great yard and view deck to take advantage of Bernal Heights' famous sunny weather. There is a separate rental unit on-site for 2 people

The space
Stay in a comfortable, well stocked, family-friendly home for your Summer vacation. Our home will welcome you and your family or group with cozy rooms, space for visiting, playing and relaxing. There are 3 bedrooms with queen beds, one of which also has a twin bed. Great deck with views and fantastic backyard with outdoor table, seating, gas firepit. You'll love our safe, clean, central and quaint neighborhood as a base for exploring the city and local experiences.
neighborhood_overview: Our home is in Bernal Heights. We are on the North-West corner, and our home has a view of both Twin Peaks and Downtown. Bernal Heights is hilly, with great views, some steep streets, stairways and tiny parks tucked into side streets. From the park at the top of our hill, there is a 360-degree view of the City, including the bay, the Bay Bridge, the Golden Gate bridge, Twin Peaks, Downtown, Mt Diablo and south to the airport. During baseball season fireworks are often visible from our hill. There is a very sweet commercial street with restaurants, shops and a library. Several parks are nearby for strolling, playing, picnicking and dogs. Our neighborhood is south of the Mission neighborhood, but still within walking distance of the lively nightlife there. It is quieter and cleaner than some of the Mission streets, but not so far from the center that anything is difficult to get to.

name: The Painted Man- SF Historic Victorian Mansion
description:
Please contact me before reserving. I do not accept instant bookings.

The Covid 19 pandemic has changed all of our lives. Keeping everyone free of germs at The Painted Man has always been the first priority.
Disinfecting the entire home is part of the usual cleaning routine for housekeeping prior to the Covid19 outbreak. Gloves are always worn to clean.

The space
Built in 1893 by renowned architects Keenan & Cranston(grandfather of Senator Alan Cranston), this Victorian is BROTHER to the world famous Painted Ladies 2 blocks away at Historic Alamo Square park. This well preserved 4 level Queen Ann Victorian Mansion retains its period details but is also updated with all modern amenities. Grand 3 level staircase, huge double parlors and beautiful parquet wood flooring. Total bedroom count 8 plus 4.5 baths on 4 levels. 10 beds total. More pics on F B and floor plan.

Guest access
Guest have access to all four levels.
neighborhood_overview: The Painted Man is located in the heart of the city, walkable to the city's hippest restaurants, shopping and parks, Pacific Heights, Hayes Valley, Lower Haight, Nopa, and Golden Gate park. Just steps away to many restaurants, cafes, upscale shops, and entertainment venues (SF Jazz, The Independent, The Fillmore, Symphony, Ballet, Opera. The Alamo Square neighborhood is characterized by Victorian architecture that was left largely untouched by the urban renewal projects in other parts of the Western Addition. Alamo Square Park, the neighborhood's focal point and namesake, consists of four city blocks at the top of a hill overlooking much of downtown San Francisco, with a number of large and architecturally distinctive mansions along the perimeter, including the "Painted Ladies", a well-known postcard motif.
host_about: My family has been in San Francisco since 1944. I love my home town and know it very well. I am happy and excited to share my home with guest from all over!!

name: Potrero Hill Sunset Retreat
description:
Great private flat high on a hill with sunset views and quiet neighbors. Easy access to freeways, bus service and Uber and Lyft. Minutes from downtown. Small patio off front entry for exclusive use of guests.

Excellent location to get away, rest, or access all that the city has to offer in the way of restaurants, nightlife and exploring the natural beauty of the Bay Area.

Great very clean retreat for business or holiday travelers. 30 DAY MINIMUM STAY.

The space
This flat is the entire top unit of a duplex/home with itÃ¢â¬â¢s own entrance, separate keyless front door entry, living room, bathroom, 2 bedrooms (1 large and 1 small), bathroom, full kitchen, sunroom and small balcony off back which over sees the view out the back side of the house. For an additional fee there is an optional third bedroom in the loft/attic with ladder access.

This is also a small patio with table and chairs in the front of your entry for your exclusive use
neighborhood_overview: Potrero Hill is one of the best neighborhoods in San Francisco, providing easy access to the 101 and 280 freeways, plus easy easy access to downtown and the Bay bridge to the East Bay. It is away from the noisy streets and filled with a good mix of working professionals and small families. The neighborhood has some of the best weather in the city.
host_about:
Working professional. I am the General Manager of a Restoration company. We help restore the interior of residential homes when they have been damaged by fire or flood. The Bay area is a great place to experiment with all kinds of foods, my favorites being Mexican, Italian, Chinese and Vietnamese but there are endless restaurants to chose from. In my spare time, love to travel, fitness training and exploring the Bay area culturally and geographically. Love being seaside to keep myself grounded and centered.

As a host, I am readily available most times if you have an emergency, but I am big on providing you privacy. Not a late night person and keep a low profile but you will find me ready and able to help make your stay comfortable and memorable. I live below in the downstairs portion of the house with its' own entrance. 

If I had a motto to describe my approach to life it is simple: Treat others the way I would want to be treated.

Turn east and head to Fort Mason, Fisherman's Wharf and onto the Embarcadero. Turn west to The Palace of Fine Arts, Crissy Field, the Presidio, and right over the Golden Gate Bridge. host_about:
'Not all who wander are lost.' I love this quote. 
I am that wanderer, incredibly lucky to be infected with the passion and audacity to travel often and solo. 
I was born and raised in San Francisco. I am a native. I love my city. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve watched it evolve. But I have also left it many times in my youth. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left it to study abroad in France. Best decision of my college life! I backpacked solo around western Europe. 
IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left SF when I was in the military and stationed around our country. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve also driven as far north as Niagara Falls.
Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.
I am cursed with this blessing of being unceasingly interested in people. I love meeting people. I love hearing stories. And I love writing them. 
As I review my lifeÃ¢â¬â¢s experiences, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve come upon one very simple realization, that proclaimed secret of success. It is merely this: Ã¢â¬ËSay what you will do and do what you will say.Ã¢â¬â¢
The prolific Seth Godin, talented blogger said creativity isnÃ¢â¬â¢t the most important part. What counts is being able to ship! Ship on time. And ship again. And again. And again.

neighborhood_overview: The Inner Sunset is a wonderful San Francisco neighborhood filled with coffee shops,  bakeries, cozy bars, a great bookstore, and lots of small restaurants.  We're happy to share our favorites.  Every Sunday morning there's an outstanding farmer's market one block away between 8th and 9th Avenues just south of Irving Street. Before we had kids, my wife and I traveled extensively -- to the Middle East and North Africa, East Africa, Central America, India, Southeast Asia, and Europe.  We also loved to ski, snowboard, and go backpacking.  With two little ones, we stay close to home and enjoy all the great things our neighborhood, city, and region have to offer.

Hi my name is Hareg, I have been living in San Francisco for the past 27 years.  I love the Bay Area.

It's just a short walk down the hill from the house to Precita Park and the Mission.

The space
I completely remodeled the house in the first half of 2013. My home offers a clean, minimalist, and modern aesthetic. host_about:
'Not all who wander are lost.' I love this quote. 
I am that wanderer, incredibly lucky to be infected with the passion and audacity to travel often and solo. 
I was born and raised in San Francisco. I am a native. I love my city. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve watched it evolve. But I have also left it many times in my youth. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left it to study abroad in France. Best decision of my college life! I backpacked solo around western Europe. 
IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left SF when I was in the military and stationed around our country. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve also driven as far north as Niagara Falls.
Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.
I am cursed with this blessing of being unceasingly interested in people. I love meeting people. I love hearing stories. And I love writing them. 
As I review my lifeÃ¢â¬â¢s experiences, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve come upon one very simple realization, that proclaimed secret of success. It is merely this: Ã¢â¬ËSay what you will do and do what you will say.Ã¢â¬â¢
The prolific Seth Godin, talented blogger said creativity isnÃ¢â¬â¢t the most important part. What counts is being able to ship! Ship on time. And ship again. And again. And again.

host_about:
Hi there,
I am a healer, working with Hospice. I am inspired to drink life up, understanding that there is a finite amount of life to be had. I love to travel. My last amazing journey was to the Amazon. Even more memorable than the visual aspects of that trip were the auditory surprises. In addition to the contant vibrational buzzing and hissing in the air, I have 2 words for you, especially if you get to the Amazon: "Howler Monkeys". They truly sound like I imagine dinosaurs would sound. Apparently they get such volume and monster howl from a hole in a bone in their throats. Must be heard to be believed. But I digress! I'm a weekly dancer, pulling out the boots for two step, the retro wear for East Coast swing, and I waltz every chance I get no matter what I'm wearing. I love beautiful found objects. I write poetry and short stories. I have a private psychotherapy practice and teach mindfulness to people who are interested in more resiliency, more ZEST!  But I bet if you talked to my friends, they'd note the overall goofy, delighted way I like to carry on with life in general. As Helen Keller said, "Life is a banquet, but most of us are starving to death." So I invite you to come to my home and take a big bite out of life. The time is now.
