name: Sunset Ocean Studio
description:
Welcome to our Outer Sunset home! This studio, with a private entrance and bathroom (newly remodeled December 2020!), is on the lower level of the house that my wife, small dog and I live in. It's a simple and sweet bedroom with a private bathroom and shower. There's a mini-fridge, Nespresso machine, and electric tea kettle but no kitchen or cooking facilities. There are a lot of great restaurants and coffee shops in the neighborhood though.

The space
We've worked hard to make this little studio space comfy and stylish. It has a lot of light, some nice plants, and a Nespresso machine for your morning coffee. ItÃ¢â¬â¢s the perfect home base to explore San Francisco!

We do live upstairs and you will be able to hear us walk around sometimes as itÃ¢â¬â¢s an old house with slightly creepy floors. We do try our best to be respectful with noise and offer earplugs and a noise machine.

Guest access
You will have access to the studio bedroom only
neighborhood_overview:
The Outer Sunset is truly a hidden gem (though less so every year) and one of the great neighborhoods of San Francisco. It has a laid back beach/surfer vibe but is still only a 10-20 minute Uber to pretty much any other neighborhood in the city. We are about a 10 minute walk to either the beach or Golden Gate Park. If you leave your window open at night you can hear the waves crashing!

The neighborhood is quiet and residential but there are still tons of cool bars and restaurants within a short walk. The Noriega strip is a 2 minute walk (Devil's Teeth, Toyose, Flanahan's, Noriega Produce), Judah is 10 minutes (Outer Lands, Trouble Coffee, Andytown Coffee), and Taraval is about a 15 minute walk (Riptide, Underdogs, Avenues Coffee). The Noriega Chinatown near Safeway is also under a 10 minute walk away and has tons of great Chinese dining option (Dim Sum, BBQ, bakery, etc.).

This is a great neighborhood if you want something more laidback and outside of the hustle
host_about: My partner Kayla, our dog Crosby and I split time between San Francisco and Missoula, Montana. I work in software and she's an elementary school teacher. We love to travel, meet new people, and enjoy time in nature! We've also both lived and traveled abroad extensively and always love learning about new places and cultures.

host_about:

I have lived in various cities in the United States (where I'm from), as well as London, Buenos Aires, and Guatemala. neighborhood_overview: Bayview, just south of Islais Creek, is a community intent on reinventing itself as an artist's colony and gardening mecca. Both the Hunters Point Shipyard Artists Open Studio and Flora Grubb Gardens are cases in point. The neighborhood takes pride in its public and backyard gardens, and the San Francisco Produce Market provides local produce to many of San Francisco's finest restaurants. Three-quarters of the residents are loyal homeowners, many of whom have developed the Quesada Garden Initiative. This community-building effort started with a few neighbors beautifying Quesada Avenue and has blossomed into an award-winning project and serves as a model for communities across the nation. Properties are still affordable and comprised primarily of single-family residences. Architecture is a smorgasbord with some renovated projects, colorful stucco homes and Victorians.

host_about:
Greetings from Noelle and George!

We both grew up in the Bay Area and are college sweethearts having both majored in biological sciences. We chose to live and raise a family which includes our three children in San Francisco because of the beautiful landscape, amazing culture and diversity, priceless climate and lets not forget exploring this beautiful city through the iconic cable car rides.

As a family we enjoy spending most of our time outdoors which includes hiking in the Marin Headlands, breezy walks along Ocean Beach, as well as biking in Golden Gate Park to name a few. Camping is a major part of our summer routine in Lake Tahoe, Yosemite National Park, and Camp Mendocino. We also enjoy Lake Tahoe during the winter months for skiing and snowboarding. Noelle and I are also avid sports fans and LOVE attending San Francisco Giants, Oakland Athletics, Golden State Warriors, San Francisco Forty Niners, Oakland Raiders and San Jose Shark games with our children and friends. Our weekends are also consumed with youth sports as our children play on baseball, basketball, golf, and swimming teams.

 We are lucky enough to live in an area which embraces the arts and we are just a short stroll away from the many music festivals which San Francisco has to offer and a few of our favorite events to attend are the Blue Grass Festival and Outside Lands both in Golden Gate Park. 

San Francisco offers a variety of multi-cultural cuisine all within a short distance from each other whether it be a walk, drive or door step away. Some of our favorites include, fresh seafood, Pho, Mission-style burritos, Korean BBQ, Cioppino, or exploring our palates with tasting world renowned wine and cheese at the Ferry Building!

description:

We are located in a quiet residential neighborhood within walking distance of 24th Street, the Castro and Mission Districts.
Note: All of the 190+ reviews on my profile are applicable to this home.

The space
The top two floors of our home include a living room, dining room (separated with pocket doors), a fully equipped kitchen, two large bedrooms, a bathroom, deck and shared enclosed garden. The bathroom has a large clawfoot tub where you can relax for a long bath or take a shower. There are two large bedrooms upstairs with the bathroom in between. The rooms are bright and spacious with windows. Each room has an empty closet, dresser and nightstand so you can unpack an

neighborhood_overview:
Sunnyside is a quiet, family-oriented neighborhood located just south of Twin Peaks. Peaceful in the early mornings and at night.

1. Enjoy walking or biking in the hills that occupy nearby Westwood, Monterey Heights, and St. Francis Woods.
2. Eat or shop at nearby West Portal, Ocean Avenue, or Glen Park.
3. A Safeway is open late is located on the same block.
4. Whole Foods is a 3 minute drive away.
5. A pizza parlor is on the corner.
6. Railroad Espresso is two blocks away.
7. A string of restaurants line adjacent Monterey Boulevard.
8. Stonestown Galleria, a major mall, is a 10 minute drive away.
9. A playground is a block away, Sunnyside Playground is 3 blocks away, and Sunnyside Conservatory is a 8 minute walk.

New mattress were just purchased along with rugs for all the spaces. Downstairs in the living/dining/kitchen, there's plenty of space for four to eat and hang out. There's also a brand new washer/dryer combo in the half bath on the same level.

Bernal Heights retains tons of San Francisco character. It has charming cafes and stores, and is a quick ride to other neighborhoods. host_about:

We are currently hosting in our primary home in San Francisco and love to provide families with a comfortable, fun and welcoming space when they are visiting our city.  We love meeting people, experiencing new cultures and sharing our space. 

I consider myself extraordinarily lucky to have been born and raised in the most beautiful city in the world - San Francisco - and I have always loved sharing it with visitors.  Since I'm an active person, I fully take advantage of all of the open spaces and trails that the SF bay area has to offer and I love taking visitors on hikes, walks, and bike rides. Let us know if you have any questions about your visit to SF or if our home might be a good fit for you!

Sunnyside is a quiet, family-oriented neighborhood located just south of Twin Peaks. Peaceful in the early mornings and at night.

1. Enjoy walking or biking in the hills that occupy nearby Westwood, Monterey Heights, and St. Francis Woods.
2. Eat or shop at nearby West Portal, Ocean Avenue, or Glen Park.
3. A Safeway is open late is located on the same block.
4. Whole Foods is a 3 minute drive away.
5. A pizza parlor is on the corner.
6. Railroad Espresso is two blocks away.
7. A string of restaurants line adjacent Monterey Boulevard.
8. Stonestown Galleria, a major mall, is a 10 minute drive away.
9. A playground is a block away, Sunnyside Playground is 3 blocks away, and Sunnyside Conservatory is a 8 minute walk.

Our home is a clean, modern 3BD/2BA with an incredible view. Spot whales over breakfast, enjoy long weekend walks along the Great Highway, or have a fire in the garden under the stars and seagulls.

Work from a sun-filled office with a standing desk, monitor and ergonomic chair and get your feet in the sand 15 seconds from home.

The space
If you have kids, let us know and we can leave toys or make special accommodations for sleeping & eating. We have all the gear! : )

- a longer walk to Sloat for the SF Zoo and more cafes and restaurants
- A short 5-minute drive to Fort Funston hiking
- Convenient 15-minute drive to big box stores (Target, HomeDepot, etc)

neighborhood_overview:
Potrero Hill is a neighborhood with a perfect SF vibe. It is residential and yet very close to the main attractions in the city. McKinley Park is a block from the house with great views and a big playground for the kids. Next to the park a beautiful community garden where the sunsets are breathtaking.
Around the corner Chiotras a very convenient Grocery Store. A cozy deli known for its sandwiches. Enjoy breakfast in Plow one of the most famous places in SF to have brunch. Before dinner enjoy a glass of wine at Ruby an organic natural winery then pick from a verity of restaurants around. French, Mexican, American, Japanese, Peruvian etc. Goat hill pizza is a traditional sf spot since 1975 making the best sourdough pies in the city. Thinkers Cafe opens early and is just a few blocks away. Have a tour at the historic Anchor Brewing Company stablished since 1896 followed by a tasting session.

I have a very close connection with friends and family. I adore animals and nature.
I'm very respectful, honest, tolerant and kind with others.

host_about:
'Not all who wander are lost.' I love this quote. 
I am that wanderer, incredibly lucky to be infected with the passion and audacity to travel often and solo. 
I was born and raised in San Francisco. I am a native. I love my city. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve watched it evolve. But I have also left it many times in my youth. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left it to study abroad in France. Best decision of my college life! I backpacked solo around western Europe. 
IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left SF when I was in the military and stationed around our country. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve also driven as far north as Niagara Falls.
Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.
I am cursed with this blessing of being unceasingly interested in people. I love meeting people. I love hearing stories. And I love writing them. 
As I review my lifeÃ¢â¬â¢s experiences, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve come upon one very simple realization, that proclaimed secret of success. It is merely this: Ã¢â¬ËSay what you will do and do what you will say.Ã¢â¬â¢
The prolific Seth Godin, talented blogger said creativity isnÃ¢â¬â¢t the most important part. What counts is being able to ship! Ship on time. And ship again. And again. And again.

Easy freeway access, close to Orpheum theater and City Hall. Harvest Urban Market is a block away.

SoMa, a thriving neighborhood, and hotbed of tech entrepreneurs and professionals. Bars, clubs, art spaces and cafÃÂ©s seem to be popping up in SoMa every day, transforming the once-industrial neighborhood into a thriving new scene for those who want to live in the hub of The City and enjoy a bit of edge.

Standing ornate and stately on its own tree-lined plaza, San Francisco City Hall is the centerpiece of the neighborhood called Civic Center. Adjacent United Nations Plaza is named for the charter that established the United Nations in 1945, signed at Herbst Theater in the War Memorial Veterans Building. neighborhood_overview: Mission Terrace is a friendly and safe community south of San Francisco downtown. It shares the same intimate vibe of its more central neighbors. neighborhood_overview:
Towering above Noe Valley on the north and Glen Canyon to the south, the neighborhood of Diamond Heights offers some of the best views in the city. Developed in the 1960s, this is a quiet, peaceful residential district tucked along the streets that wind beneath eucalyptus. Charming, tree canopied stairway walks connect the streets, and provide steep short cuts and breathtaking views.

The neighborhood has the laid back feel of a suburb within the city limits. Home to approximately 100 prized Eichlers built on seven distinct floor plans, Diamond Heights is an undiscovered gem.

It's centrally located to much of what the city has on offer. Noe Valley is a 15-minute walk, and downtown San Francisco a short 10 minute drive. The Mission is just a 5 minute drive away.

Plentiful street parking in the neighborhood.
host_about: We are Geoff and Tati, a San Francisco based couple. Our Diamond Heights home embodies our passion for mid century design and we look forward to sharing it with you.

neighborhood_overview:
Noe Valley feels like a small town despite its centrality in San Francisco, making it a coveted neighborhood. As the name suggests it's bordered by hills, giving it an intimate feel. 24th Street is its main drag, full of artisanal goods stores, yoga places, and a Whole Foods.

It has a very cohesive community feeling, as evidenced by the brand new town square that sits off of 24th Street; this is the result of an organized effort by residents to turn a parking lot into a space to gather and relax in the sun. The town square now houses the wonderful Saturday FarmerÃ¢â¬â¢s Market, which features live music, food carts and local produce.

Noe Valley is sunny and clean-cut, with lots of pedestrians, many with strollers and dogs. Bordered on the north by The Castro and Dolores Heights, on the east by The Mission, on the south by Glen Park, and on the west by Diamond Heights and Twin Peaks.

Its tall ceilings give a spacious feel

2) Every Monday, Wednesday and Fridays from 9-10am the Japanese Tea Garden is free, so this is a fav spot to enjoy some pastries and green tea or if you prefer some miso soup and Hojicha tea--breakfast of champions!

3) Walk a bit further through the park, passing the aquarium, the famous Shakespeare garden, the botanical gardens, and over to 9th Ave where you'll find a most delectable bakery/cafe...perhaps you've heard of it? name: Cozy Carriage House in the Heart of Cow Hollow
description:
This house is a compact but very functional little carriage house that has been around for at least 120+ years, survived the 1906 San Francisco earthquake and fires and has watched San Francisco change over the years. The space

The patio is shared between myself and the two other units that face the sidewalk. We are tucked in between several other buildings which ensures security and quiet during the night.

Guest access
Guests can access the property through the side walkway which has a coded lock and makes package delivery easy and secure. The patio is a shared common space.

description: Beautiful 1-bedroom perfect for the family who wants to be part of the local action.
host_about:
I'm married and when I'm not traveling on business, I travel everywhere with my husband and 2 toddler kids. We LOVE exploring new cities, great food, and do tons of outdoors stuff like hiking, mountain biking & snowboarding, to name a few. When we travel, we prefer to hang out with the locals and learn more about what it's like living in a particular place. Doing the touristy thing can get old. 

To get us as guests, rest assured, we treat every place we stay in like it's our own. We love cleanliness and tidyness and we have always left our accommodations in the same or better condition than when we arrived, be it a hotel, or a vacation rental. 

We had opened up our home to international students and travelers and we welcomed them like they were part of our family. We also own 2 rental properties and we consider our tenants to be our partners in taking care of our homes. Being a host and a landlord has definitely allowed us to see the airbnb home rental process from both angles. 

We believe that we what we put out in the world, is what we get back.  So we aim to treat others as we would like to be treated, and that includes having respect for other people's properties.

We are in the geographic center of the city, close to public transportation (bus, muni train) and a block away from a major tech bus route. Our house is at the intersection of several of the most beautiful and active neighborhoods of the city, including Alamo Square, NOPA, Lower Haight, and the Haight Ashbury. If you are a runner (like us!) you can easily run to the Golden Gate Park (less than a mile away). You can run through this park all the way to Ocean Beach if you are in the mood for an 8 mile round trip run.

Our immediate neighborhood includes several cafes within a block, in addition to premium grocery stores, one of the best stretches of restaurants and retail in the city, and ... some amazing bars and record stores. A list of some of our favorites within walking distance will be placed in the unit.

Walk to work to FiDi, stroll to dimsum and the best spicy Chinese food in SF, or enjoy excellent Italian seafood in the heart of North Beach. Walking distance to transit for work, or a ride on the cable car. Ride your bike to the Presidio, Crissy Field, or over the Golden Gate Bridge into Marin.

Steps from both Hayes Valley and the Divisadero corridor with stunning views of the Painted Ladies and the city from the Master bedroom, this home is a special find. The house boasts 3 bedrooms, 3 baths, a library (with a one-of-a-kind Victorian ceiling), a playroom that can double as an additional bedroom and an office/home gym. It also has a large backyard with beautiful flowers and a comfortable seating area.

The space
This historic home was build in 1890 and has been painstakingly restored. The front room and master bedroom have views of Alamo Square (including the famous Painted Ladies). There is ample seating for groups, a large dining room table, a large kitchen with an island, and a large backyard with seating and a barbecue. If desired, the house can also be outfitted for young kids, with standing towers, high chairs, etc. The home gym in the back of the house has a Peleton

neighborhood_overview:
Midtown Terrace is a quiet residential neighborhood perched on top of San Francisco. This elevated area lends itself to some of the most stunning views of the entire city. Surrounded by greenery and lush trees you get the closest view possible of the famous city landmark, 'Sutro Tower'. A quick walk to Twin peaks reveals the panoramic city view. There are multiple hiking trails a short distance away from our studio including Twin Peaks, Mount Sutro, Mount Davidson, Corona Heights and Glen Park Canyon. This area is located in the center of the city and close to popular areas, such as Golden Gate Park, Noe Valley, Castro and Haight Ashbury neighborhoods.
There is a fantastic Children's Museum - Randall Museum not too far away, it's a must-do for those traveling with children.
